<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Cameron, Duncan. A Sketch of the Nipigon Country with extracts from His Journal, 1804. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0025</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="AddHand-editors">[Journal begins]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="Gap">[&#8230;]</span> August<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The guide Started very Early with his three Canoes <span class="Gap">[&#8230;]</span>s <span class="Gap">[&#8230;]</span>re from Lake Nipigon, and at 10 OClock I sent off the 2 o<span class="AddHand-editors">[th]</span>ers, Who had Just time to get Across, when it began to blow very fresh, so that I remain'd here all day, but as the others Could go on, where they were, I did not Care much, as I Knew very well that we Could soon Overtake them<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">17<sup>th</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[W]</span>e Started Early<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[T]</span>his Day we made 10 portages, where we used to make but four, and Came through a Small Lake not above 2 Miles long, that gave the Men four Hours very hard Labour, paddling through mud, or Vaze, with not above two Inches Water on the top of it, and the Mud riseing on each side above the Maitres, with a Stench that was ready to Stiffle us<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[T]</span>his is only the begining, for we have nothing Else but muddy Lakes, and portages from here to Osnaburgh, and God Knows when we'll get Out of them, although the distance is not above 25 Leagues<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[W]</span>e Camped at Portage de Petite Chute<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">18<sup>th</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Nothing but Paddling through Mud, and Carrying</p>

